facts Conserving health in early modern culture documents the profound impact which ideas about healthy living had on daily practices as well as on intellectual life and the material world in this period. In both countries staying healthy was understood as depending on the careful management of the six ‘Non-Naturals’: the air one breathed, food and drink, excretions, sleep, exercise and repose, and the ‘passions of the soul’. To a close scrutiny, however, models of prevention differed considerably in Italy and England, reflecting country-specific cultural, political and medical contexts and different confessional backgrounds.The following two chapters are available open access on a CC-BY-NC-ND license here: http://www.oapen.org/search?identifier=6331803 'Ordering the infant': caring for newborns in early modern England - Leah Astbury4 'She sleeps well and eats an egg': convalescent care in early modern England - Hannah Newton  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth behavior. 0aPublic healthzGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aPublic healthzItalyxHistoryy16th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aGalenic-Hippocratic tradition.  aItaly.  aNeapolitan environment.  aNon-Naturals.  ababies.  achildbirth.  aconvalescent care.  aconvalescents.  adaily practices.  aearly modern culture.  ahealth conservation.  ahealthy living.  aintellectual life.  amotion and rest.  apregnancy.  awomen.1 aAjmar, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAstbury, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastiglione, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavallo, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavallo, Sandra, eeditor.4